The Luck Engine

This is the part I find most interesting.

You’ve used the word “luck” for a long time, but in engineering terms it can be reframed as increasing exposure to valuable opportunities while filtering noise.

Rather than treating luck as mystical, Pantheon could define it operationally:

Increase the probability of encountering valuable, previously unrecognized opportunities by systematically exploring high-potential regions under uncertainty.

That leads to a repeatable loop:

Observe
↓
Estimate novelty
↓
Estimate value
↓
Estimate uncertainty
↓
Explore
↓
Validate
↓
Archive

Over many iterations, the system becomes better at finding “lucky” discoveries because it spends more effort where the expected value of exploration is high.

